{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585215","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585215"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:06:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:06:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14935"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14935"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.63,0.16,0.19,0,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7623"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66425"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7623","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7623"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14935"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51876"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"5495"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"},{"type":"tags","id":"8095"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18637"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18640"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66425","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66425"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EBacteriophages are viruses that infect bacteria. They have been studied as potential therapeutic agents against bacterial infections.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes bacteriophages?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Temperate phages integrate into the bacterial chromosome","Phages replicate inside eukaryotic cells","Phages always cause immediate bacterial lysis","Phages cannot transfer bacterial genes","Phages require human cells to reproduce"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETemperate phages integrate into the bacterial chromosome\u003C/strong\u003E during lysogeny. The viral DNA becomes a prophage and replicates along with the bacterial genome until conditions trigger the lytic cycle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhages replicate inside eukaryotic cells\u003C/strong\u003E - Bacteriophages are specific to bacterial cells and cannot infect eukaryotic cells\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhages always cause immediate bacterial lysis\u003C/strong\u003E - While lytic phages cause cell lysis, temperate phages can establish lysogeny without killing the host\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhages cannot transfer bacterial genes\u003C/strong\u003E - Phages can transfer DNA between bacteria through transduction\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhages require human cells to reproduce\u003C/strong\u003E - Phages only replicate within bacterial cells\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding bacteriophage biology is important as these viruses play roles in bacterial evolution through horizontal gene transfer and are being investigated as alternatives to antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Bacteriophages are viruses that specifically infect and replicate within bacterial cells.","Temperate bacteriophages can integrate their DNA into the bacterial chromosome as prophages during lysogeny.","Bacteriophages can transfer genetic material between bacteria through transduction."],"references":["Kasman LM, Porter LD. Bacteriophages. 2022 Sep 26. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29630237.","Azam AH, Tan XE, Veeranarayanan S, Kiga K, Cui L. Bacteriophage Technology and Modern Medicine. Antibiotics (Basel). 2021 Aug 18;10(8):999. doi: 10.3390/antibiotics10080999. PMID: 34439049; PMCID: PMC8388951.","Hatfull GF, Dedrick RM, Schooley RT. Phage Therapy for Antibiotic-Resistant Bacterial Infections. Annu Rev Med. 2022 Jan 27;73:197-211. doi: 10.1146/annurev-med-080219-122208. Epub 2021 Aug 24. PMID: 34428079."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51876"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14935"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51876","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51876"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-30T08:53:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-30T08:54:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7623"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66425"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{